      <section class="section-block">
        <div class="container">
          <p class="section-question">How do Bitcoin Script and OP_CHECKMULTISIG work?</p>
          <h2 id="a-scripts" >Bitcoin Script and Multisig Transactions</h2>
          <div class="guide-text">
            <p>Multisig in Bitcoin is enforced at the protocol level through <strong>Bitcoin Script</strong> &mdash; a stack-based programming language embedded in every transaction. The spending conditions are not enforced by wallet software; they are enforced by every node on the network.</p>
            <h3>OP_CHECKMULTISIG</h3>
            <p>The original multisig mechanism uses the <code>OP_CHECKMULTISIG</code> opcode. A 2-of-3 redeem script looks like:</p>
            <div class="guide-code-block">
              <div class="guide-code-block__label">2-of-3 Multisig Redeem Script</div>
              <div class="guide-code-block__body"><span class="kw">OP_2</span>
  <span class="st">&lt;pubkey_1&gt;</span>
  <span class="st">&lt;pubkey_2&gt;</span>
  <span class="st">&lt;pubkey_3&gt;</span>
<span class="kw">OP_3</span>
<span class="kw">OP_CHECKMULTISIG</span></div>
            </div>
            <p>When spending, the witness/scriptSig must provide exactly M valid signatures corresponding to M of the N listed public keys.</p>
            <h3>Script Wrapping (P2SH, P2WSH)</h3>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>P2SH (Pay-to-Script-Hash)</strong> &mdash; the redeem script is hashed; only the hash appears in the output. The full script is revealed at spending time. Addresses start with <code>3</code>.</li>
              <li><strong>P2WSH (Pay-to-Witness-Script-Hash)</strong> &mdash; SegWit version. Moves the witness data outside the base transaction, reducing effective size and fees. Addresses start with <code>bc1q</code> (longer than single-sig bc1q addresses).</li>
              <li><strong>P2SH-P2WSH</strong> &mdash; nested SegWit for backward compatibility. The outer P2SH wraps an inner P2WSH. Addresses start with <code>3</code>.</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="callout callout-info">
              <span class="callout-label">On-Chain Fingerprint</span>
              Traditional multisig reveals the quorum policy (M-of-N) and all public keys when a <a href="<%= langPrefix %>/guides/wallet-anatomy#a-utxo">UTXO</a> is spent. This is a privacy consideration &mdash; an observer can see that the output was controlled by a multisig setup and identify the exact policy. Taproot (see below) addresses this limitation.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section-block">
        <div class="container">
          <p class="section-question">What are output descriptors and how do they help multisig recovery?</p>
          <h2 id="a-descriptors" >Output Descriptors and Wallet Recovery</h2>
          <div class="guide-text">
            <p><strong>Output descriptors</strong> (defined in BIPs 380-386) are a standardized way to describe the spending conditions for a set of addresses. For multisig wallets, the descriptor encodes everything needed to reconstruct the wallet:</p>
            <div class="guide-code-block">
              <div class="guide-code-block__label">Output Descriptor (2-of-3)</div>
              <div class="guide-code-block__body"><span class="fn">wsh</span><span class="op">(</span><span class="fn">sortedmulti</span><span class="op">(</span><span class="nm">2</span>,
  <span class="op">[</span><span class="st">fingerprint_1/48h/0h/0h/2h</span><span class="op">]</span>xpub_1<span class="op">/</span><span class="nm">0</span><span class="op">/*</span>,
  <span class="op">[</span><span class="st">fingerprint_2/48h/0h/0h/2h</span><span class="op">]</span>xpub_2<span class="op">/</span><span class="nm">0</span><span class="op">/*</span>,
  <span class="op">[</span><span class="st">fingerprint_3/48h/0h/0h/2h</span><span class="op">]</span>xpub_3<span class="op">/</span><span class="nm">0</span><span class="op">/*</span>
<span class="op">))</span><span class="cm">#checksum</span></div>
            </div>
            <h3>Descriptor Components</h3>
            <ul>
              <li><code>wsh()</code> &mdash; wrapping type (Witness Script Hash = native SegWit)</li>
              <li><code>sortedmulti(2, ...)</code> &mdash; quorum of 2, with keys sorted lexicographically (BIP67)</li>
              <li><code>[fingerprint/path]xpub</code> &mdash; each cosigner's extended public key with its derivation path and master fingerprint</li>
              <li><code>/0/*</code> &mdash; receive addresses (change uses <code>/1/*</code>)</li>
              <li><code>#checksum</code> &mdash; descriptor checksum for integrity verification</li>
            </ul>
            <h3>Recovery Requirements</h3>
            <p>To fully recover a multisig wallet, you need:</p>
            <ol>
              <li><strong>M seed phrases</strong> (for signing capability)</li>
              <li><strong>All N xpubs</strong> (to reconstruct the address set)</li>
              <li><strong>The quorum policy</strong> (M-of-N)</li>
              <li><strong>The derivation paths</strong> for each cosigner</li>
              <li><strong>The script type</strong> (P2SH, P2WSH, P2TR)</li>
            </ol>
            <div class="callout callout-warning">
              <span class="callout-label">Backup Strategy</span>
              Store the full wallet descriptor alongside every seed phrase backup. Without the descriptor, having M seed phrases is insufficient &mdash; you won't know which addresses to derive or what script template to use. Each backup location should contain: one seed phrase + the complete descriptor file.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section-block">
        <div class="container">
          <p class="section-question">How does Taproot improve multisig privacy with MuSig2?</p>
          <h2 id="a-taproot" >Taproot Multisig and MuSig2</h2>
          <div class="guide-text">
            <p>Bitcoin's Taproot upgrade (activated November 2021) introduced <strong><a href="<%= langPrefix %>/guides/wallet-anatomy#a-ecdsa">Schnorr</a> signatures</strong> and <strong>MAST (Merkelized Abstract Syntax Trees)</strong>, which fundamentally improve multisig privacy and efficiency.</p>
            <h3>Key Path Spending with MuSig2</h3>
            <p><strong>MuSig2</strong> is a Schnorr-based multi-signature scheme where all N participants cooperatively produce a single aggregate signature. On-chain, this is <strong>indistinguishable</strong> from a regular single-signature Taproot transaction:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Only one 64-byte Schnorr signature appears in the witness</li>
              <li>The output looks identical to a single-key P2TR output</li>
              <li>No public keys, quorum policies, or script complexity is revealed</li>
              <li>Transaction fees are identical to single-sig Taproot</li>
            </ul>
            <h3>Script Path Fallback</h3>
            <p>If not all N signers are available (e.g., for an M-of-N threshold where M &lt; N), the transaction can fall back to a <strong>Tapscript leaf</strong> that encodes the threshold policy. Only the specific branch used is revealed on-chain; unused branches remain hidden in the Merkle tree.</p>
            <div class="guide-diagram">
              <div class="guide-diagram__title">Taproot Output Structure</div>
              <div class="diagram-tree">
                <div class="diagram-node diagram-node--root">Taproot Output</div>
                <div class="diagram-connector"></div>
                <div class="diagram-branch">
                  <div class="diagram-branch-item">
                    <div class="diagram-connector"></div>
                    <div class="diagram-node diagram-node--highlight">Key Path</div>
                    <div class="diagram-label">MuSig2(all N keys)</div>
                    <div class="diagram-label">cooperative &middot; most private</div>
                  </div>
                  <div class="diagram-branch-item">
                    <div class="diagram-connector"></div>
                    <div class="diagram-node">Script Path (MAST)</div>
                    <div class="diagram-connector"></div>
                    <div class="diagram-branch">
                      <div class="diagram-branch-item">
                        <div class="diagram-connector"></div>
                        <div class="diagram-node">Leaf 1</div>
                        <div class="diagram-label">2-of-3 threshold</div>
                      </div>
                      <div class="diagram-branch-item">
                        <div class="diagram-connector"></div>
                        <div class="diagram-node">Leaf 2</div>
                        <div class="diagram-label">timelock + key D</div>
                      </div>
                      <div class="diagram-branch-item">
                        <div class="diagram-connector"></div>
                        <div class="diagram-node">Leaf 3</div>
                        <div class="diagram-label">3-of-5 threshold</div>
                      </div>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="callout callout-tip">
              <span class="callout-label">Privacy Advantage</span>
              With Taproot + MuSig2, a multisig setup looks exactly like a regular payment on-chain. This is a massive privacy improvement over P2WSH multisig, where the script reveals the exact M-of-N policy and all involved public keys upon spending.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section-block">
        <div class="container">
          <p class="section-question">How do you manage keys and vendor diversity in multisig?</p>
          <h2 id="a-key-management" >Key Management and Vendor Diversity</h2>
          <div class="guide-text">
            <p>The security of a multisig setup depends not just on the quorum policy but on the <strong>independence and diversity</strong> of the keys.</p>
            <h3>Vendor Diversity Principle</h3>
            <p>Use hardware wallets from <strong>different manufacturers</strong> for each key in your multisig setup. This protects against:</p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Firmware vulnerabilities</strong> &mdash; a zero-day exploit in one vendor's firmware can only compromise one key</li>
              <li><strong>Supply chain attacks</strong> &mdash; a compromised manufacturing batch affects only one device</li>
              <li><strong>Correlated failures</strong> &mdash; a hardware defect specific to one model doesn't affect other brands</li>
            </ul>
            <h3>Geographic Distribution</h3>
            <p>Store keys in <strong>physically separate locations</strong> to protect against:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Natural disasters (fire, flood, earthquake) destroying multiple keys</li>
              <li>Burglary or physical attack at a single location</li>
              <li>Legal seizure or government confiscation at one jurisdiction</li>
            </ul>
            <h3>Operational Independence</h3>
            <p>For organizational multisig, each key holder should:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Generate and store their key <strong>independently</strong>, without sharing the seed with others</li>
              <li>Use their <strong>own hardware</strong> and secure storage infrastructure</li>
              <li>Not have access to more than one key (violating this defeats the purpose of multisig)</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="callout callout-warning">
              <span class="callout-label">Anti-Pattern</span>
              Generating all multisig keys on the same device, storing all seeds in the same location, or having one person hold all keys reduces your multisig to an expensive single-sig with extra complexity. The entire value of multisig comes from independence between signers.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section-block">
        <div class="container">
          <p class="section-question">What are collaborative custody services and how do they work?</p>
          <h2 id="a-collaborative" >Collaborative Custody Services</h2>
          <div class="guide-text">
            <p><strong>Collaborative custody</strong> is a model where a third-party service holds one key in a multisig setup, providing recovery assistance and additional security without taking custodial control of your funds.</p>
            <h3>Typical 2-of-3 Collaborative Model</h3>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Key 1</strong> &mdash; held by you (hardware wallet)</li>
              <li><strong>Key 2</strong> &mdash; held by the collaborative custody service</li>
              <li><strong>Key 3</strong> &mdash; held by you in <a href="<%= langPrefix %>/guides/wallet-comparison#b-hot-cold">cold storage</a> (emergency recovery)</li>
            </ul>
            <p>Normal transactions require your key (Key 1) and the service's co-signature (Key 2). If the service disappears or becomes unresponsive, you recover using Keys 1 + 3. If you lose your primary device, you recover using Keys 2 + 3 (after identity verification with the service).</p>
            <h3>Evaluating Collaborative Custody</h3>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Does the service hold a minority of keys?</strong> &mdash; they should never be able to unilaterally move funds</li>
              <li><strong>Can you recover without the service?</strong> &mdash; you must be able to access funds independently using your own keys</li>
              <li><strong>Is the service open-source?</strong> &mdash; can you verify the key management and signing protocols?</li>
              <li><strong>What identity verification does the service require?</strong> &mdash; understand the trade-off between convenience and privacy</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="callout callout-info">
              <span class="callout-label">Self-Custody Preserved</span>
              A well-designed collaborative custody setup preserves <a href="<%= langPrefix %>/guides/self-sovereignty#b-what-is">self-sovereignty</a>. You always retain the ability to move funds without the service's cooperation (using your two keys). The service provides convenience and a safety net, not control.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>
    </div>

    <!-- ===== FAQ ===== -->
    <section class="section-block faq-section">
      <div class="container">
        <p class="label">[ FREQUENTLY ASKED QUESTIONS ]</p>
        <h2 >FAQ</h2>
        <div class="faq-chat">

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q-btn" type="button">
              <span>Is multisig only for Bitcoin?</span>
              <span class="faq-arrow">&rsaquo;</span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-bubble-wrap">
              <div class="faq-bubble" data-text="No, but Bitcoin has the most mature and widely tested multisig ecosystem. Ethereum supports multisig via smart contracts (like Gnosis Safe), but this is fundamentally different from Bitcoin's native script-level multisig. Other chains have varying levels of support. Bitcoin's protocol-level enforcement is considered the gold standard because it does not depend on smart contract correctness."></div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q-btn" type="button">
              <span>Are multisig transactions more expensive?</span>
              <span class="faq-arrow">&rsaquo;</span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-bubble-wrap">
              <div class="faq-bubble" data-text="Traditional multisig (P2SH, P2WSH) transactions are larger and therefore more expensive than single-sig because they must include multiple signatures and the full redeem script. A 2-of-3 P2WSH transaction is roughly 2-3x the size of a single-sig SegWit transaction. However, Taproot multisig with MuSig2 (key path spending) produces transactions the same size as single-sig Taproot, eliminating the fee premium entirely."></div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q-btn" type="button">
              <span>What happens if I lose one key in a 2-of-3 setup?</span>
              <span class="faq-arrow">&rsaquo;</span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-bubble-wrap">
              <div class="faq-bubble" data-text="You can still access your funds using the remaining two keys. However, you should immediately migrate to a new multisig setup: create a new 2-of-3 wallet with a fresh third key, then transfer all funds from the old wallet to the new one. Operating with only two keys means you have zero redundancy &mdash; losing a second key would be catastrophic."></div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q-btn" type="button">
              <span>Can I use multisig with a passphrase (25th word)?</span>
              <span class="faq-arrow">&rsaquo;</span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-bubble-wrap">
              <div class="faq-bubble" data-text="Yes. Each cosigner's seed phrase can independently have its own passphrase. This adds another layer of protection: an attacker who obtains a seed phrase backup still needs the corresponding passphrase to derive the correct key. However, this also increases backup complexity &mdash; you must track which passphrase belongs to which seed and ensure both are recoverable."></div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q-btn" type="button">
              <span>Do I need special software for multisig?</span>
              <span class="faq-arrow">&rsaquo;</span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-bubble-wrap">
              <div class="faq-bubble" data-text="You need a wallet that supports multisig coordination. Popular options include Sparrow Wallet (desktop, open-source), Nunchuk (mobile + desktop), Electrum (desktop), and Caravan (web-based, by Unchained). These tools handle the PSBT workflow: creating unsigned transactions, collecting signatures from each cosigner device, and broadcasting the fully signed transaction. Your hardware wallets handle the signing part."></div>
            </div>
          </div>

        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

